<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12005a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12005a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12005a"> 5(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> asks to eat son / Tua gives him a stone / broke molar S. Suliac</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">On raconte qu&apos;un jour il devint amoureux d&apos;une f&eacute;e qui le rendit p&egrave;re d&apos;un gros gar&ccedil;on. Quelques temps apr&egrave;s, il revenait de la chasse, et il avait tellement faim qu&apos;il demanda son fils pour le d&eacute;vorer. Prise de compassion, la nourrice ne voulut pas ob&eacute;ir; elle substitua au marmot un &eacute;norme bloc de granit, l&apos;enveloppa de langes, et le jeta dans le gosier du glouton, qui n&apos;en fit qu&apos;une bouch&eacute;e. Mais &mdash; et cela ne surprendra personne &mdash; il se brisa une molaire, et cette dent est l&apos;un des deux menhirs de Saint-Suliac. <br><font color="green">[They say that one day he fell in love with a fairy who made him the father of a fat boy. Some time later, he returned from hunting and was so hungry that he asked for his son so he could eat him. Filled with compassion, the wet nurse did not want to obey him and so she replaced the bairn with an enormous granite block, covered it in swaddling clothes and tossed it into the gullet of the glutton, for whom it was only a morsel. But &mdash; and this should come as no surprise &mdash; he broke a molar and this tooth is one of the two menhirs of Saint-Suliac.]</font> <small> l'Abb&eacute; A. Millon, <a name="AMPB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMPB"><cite title="source">Pauvres Pierres! Les Megalithes Bretons devant la science</cite></a> (n.d) 14</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
